Step 2: Push your Backend to GitHub
If your backend is only local, you'll want to create a GitHub repository for it (just like your frontend).

In the Windsurf terminal, initialize git: git init
Add your files: git add .
Commit them: git commit -m "Initial backend commit with Dockerfile"
Push to a new GitHub repo.
Step 3: Connect GitHub to Google Cloud (The "Magic" Step)
Now, instead of running gcloud commands, you can use the Google Cloud Console to set up "Continuous Deployment":

Go to the Cloud Run Console .
Click Create Service.
Select Continuously deploy from a repository.
Click Set up with Cloud Build.
Select your GitHub repository and follow the prompts to link it.
💡 The Big Benefit for Windsurf Users
Once this is set up, you stay entirely inside Windsurf.

You write your code in Windsurf.
You use Windsurf's Git integration to push your changes.
Google Cloud automatically detects the push, builds the new container, and deploys it to your live URL.
